                   Skip to main content       GOV.UK uses cookies to make the site simpler. Find out more about cookies            GOV.UK        Gender pay gap service                      BETA  This is a new service – your feedback will help us to improve it.          Search again       POUNDLAND LIMITED         Snapshot date   5 April 2017     Person responsible for employer's report   Michelle Burton (Group HR Director)     Employer's gender pay gap report   http://www.poundland.co.uk/wordpress/poundland/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/POUNDLAND-Gender-Pay-Reporting-Statement-April-2017.pdf     Address   Wellmans Road, Willenhall, West Midlands, United Kingdom, WV13 2QT     Nature of business (SIC)   Wholesale and retail trade; repair of motor vehicles and motorcycles     Employer Size   5000 to 19,999 employees          Gender pay gap report        Difference in hourly rate      About mean and median   The mean hourly rate is the average hourly wage across the entire organization so the mean gender pay gap is a measure of the difference between women’s mean hourly wage and men’s mean hourly wage.  The median hourly rate is calculated by ranking all employees from the highest paid to the lowest paid, and taking the hourly wage of the person in the middle; so the median gender pay gap is the difference between women’s median hourly wage (the middle paid woman) and men’s median hourly wage (the middle paid man).          Women’s mean hourly rate is  10.4%  lower than men’s   In other words when comparing mean hourly rates, women earn  90p  for every £1 that men earn.        Women’s median hourly rate is  0%  lower than men’s   In other words when comparing median hourly rates, women earn the same as men.            Proportion of women in each pay quartile     About quartiles   Pay quartiles are calculated by splitting all employees in an organisation into four even groups according to their level of pay.
                                Looking at the proportion of women in each quartile gives an indication of women's representation at different levels of the organisation.                    Top quartile (highest paid)         41.2% of the top quartile are women            Upper middle quartile        54.4% of the upper middle quartile are women            Lower middle quartile        76.7% of the lower middle quartile are women            Lower quartile (lowest paid)         55.7% of the lower quartile are women                 Who received bonus pay     7.7%  of women   11.2%  of men       Difference in bonus pay     Women’s mean bonus pay is  0.3%  higher than men’s   Women’s median bonus pay is  26.4%  lower than men’s                 Contact Us     Open Government Licence   All content is available under the Open Government Licence v3.0 , except where otherwise stated     © Crown copyright             